Description of Services 
 
Hematologic cancers begin in the tissues that form blood (e.g., bone marrow, cells of the immune system). Some 
examples of hematologic cancers include leukemia, lymphoma, and multiple myeloma [National Cancer Institute (NCI), 
Dictionary of Cancer Terms, 2025b]. Technologies used for molecular profiling of hematologic cancers vary and include, 
but are not limited to, tests that evaluate variations in the genes, such as Next Generation Sequencing. The amount of 
genetic material evaluated can range from a single gene to the whole exome or genome. For the purposes of this policy, 
multi-gene analysis generally refers to a gene panel containing five or more genes, though some exceptions may apply as 
noted specifically in the policy. Results of molecular profiling may assist individuals and healthcare providers with 
determining prognosis and selection of more effective and targeted cancer therapies (Chantrill et al., 2015). 
 
Clinical Evidence 
 
Multi-Gene Panel Use in Hematological Cancers 
To ascertain the clinical utility of myeloid panel next-generation sequencing (NGS), Soderquist et al. (2024) evaluated 
ordering practices, prior authorization requirements, clinical impact, and reimbursement outcomes related to 477 
individuals with known or suspected myeloid malignancies that underwent testing with either a 50-gene myeloid NGS 
panel or a 15-gene myeloproliferative neoplasm subpanel. The researchers determined that 98% (496/505) of all test 
outcomes afforded helpful clinical data; specifically, 89% of results either led to a diagnosis or clarified a potential 
diagnosis, 94% provided information regarding possible prognoses, and 19% detected a potential therapeutic target. The 
authors assert that their study results show that the use of a broad NGS panel significantly improves diagnostic and 
prognostic yield when compared to limited testing of individual genes such as JAK2, CALR, and MPL and add to the 
existing evidence supporting the broad clinical usefulness of NGS tests in individuals with myeloid neoplasias. 
 
A 2023 Hayes Molecular Test Assessment (updated 2024) evaluated the use of FoundationOne Heme
®
 (Foundation 
Medicine) to inform therapeutic options for individuals with hematologic malignancies as well as sarcomas and solid 
tumors. Five studies addressing clinical validity were identified. These studies, though of lower quality, showed that 32% 
to 90% of individuals had potentially actionable alterations detected by FoundationOne Heme. Three of the five studies 
reported actionable alterations that were targetable by on-label FDA-approved drugs (6% to 14% of subjects), off label 
FDA approved drugs (49% to 56% of subjects) or experimental drugs in a clinical trial (11% to 33% of subjects). 
FoundationOne Heme was not compared to other tests (such as targeted tests) or other methodologies, nor was its use in 
identifying therapeutic options it evaluated for clinical outcomes. One very poor quality study addressing clinical utility for 
FoundationOne Heme was identified, but it focused on individuals with sarcoma. The 2024 annual review of this report 
found no newly published studies meeting inclusion criteria. 
 
HM-SCREEN-Japan 01 was a multicenter study of prospective genomic profiling in individuals with either newly 
diagnosed acute myeloid leukemia (AML) or relapsed/refractory AML who were ineligible for standard therapy (Hosono et 
al., 2023; included in the 2023 Hayes Molecular Test Assessment described above). The researchers used paraffin 
embedded bone marrow clot specimens to perform NGS using FoundationOne Heme, which incorporated sequencing of 
DNA from 437 genes and RNA from 265 genes. The study’s purpose was to evaluate for the presence of molecular 
abnormalities that could potentially be targeted with novel treatment options. A total of 188 individuals from 17 institutions 
in Japan were enrolled; genetic alterations were identified in 177 participants (97.3%) and fusion transcripts were 
identified in 23.2% of participants, demonstrating the feasibility of using BM clot specimens. Both common fusion products 
(RUNX1 RUNX1T1, KMT2A) and rare rearrangements (NUP98)/rare fusion genes were identified. KIT and WT1 
mutations emerged as independent predictors of poorer overall survival and participants harboring TP53 mutations with 
variant allele frequency ≥  40% had markedly poor prognosis. In this study, FoundationOne Heme identified actionable 
mutations (FLT3 ITD/TKD, IDH1/2, DNMT3A^R822) in 38% (n = 69) of the participants, supporting targeted therapy 
selection in a relatively substantial subset. Overall, the authors concluded that genomic profiling using paraffin embedded 
bone marrow clot specimens is both practical and clinically informative, facilitating the detection of somatic mutations and 
potentially targetable alterations even in situations where fresh bone marrow samples are not available. Several of the 
authors of the publication had affiliations with laboratories associated with genetic tests and one author was a 
representative of the laboratory that manufactures the test used in this study (FoundationOne Heme). Notably, the median 
turnaround time for results was approximately 13 days, which may be too long to wait for results when urgent treatment 
decisions are needed. 
 
In a 2018 multicenter study including 2035 individuals, Grinfeld et al. sequenced coding exons from 69 identified myeloid 
cancer genes in individuals diagnosed with myeloproliferative neoplasms. Using this information, a genomic classification 
was developed to predict outcomes for individuals. In all, 33 genes had driver mutations in at least five individuals, with 
JAK2, CALR, or MPL as the only abnormality detected in 45% of participants. Volumes of driver mutations increased in 

 
