parallel with age and advancement of disease. Demographic variables, germline polymorphisms, and driver mutations 
independently predicted disease and eight genomic subgroups with distinct clinical phenotypes were defined. Ultimately, 
prognostic models which could generate tailored prediction of clinical outcomes in individuals with chronic-phase 
myeloproliferative neoplasms and myelofibrosis were created and predicted/observed outcomes correlated in internal 
cross-validation of a training group and an independent external group. The authors concluded that their characterization 
may enable personalized prediction of outcomes and better support individuals diagnosed with myeloproliferative 
neoplasms. 
 
Weinhold et al. (2016) reported clinical outcomes of gene expression profiling (GEP) in relation to treatment type for 
subgroups of individuals (n = 1217) with multiple myeloma (MM) who participated in the University of Arkansas for Medical 
Sciences Total Therapy (TT) trials. Using log-rank tests for GEP data, the researchers identified 70 genes linked to early 
disease-related death. The UAMS GEP70 risk score is based on the ratio of the mean expression level of up-regulated to 
down-regulated genes among the 70 genes. Most up-regulated genes are located on chromosome 1q, and many down-
regulated genes map to chromosome 1p. The risk-predicting test enabled the reliable identification of individuals with 
shorter durations of complete remission, event-free survival, and overall survival that constitute 10-15% of individuals with 
newly diagnosed MM. The authors indicated that the impact of treatment differs between molecular subtypes of MM and 
indicated that GEP gives important information that can help in clinical decision-making and treatment selection. They go 
on to recommend future studies investigating additional molecular approaches such as optical genome mapping and long-
range whole genome sequencing. 
 
Detection of Measurable Residual Disease (MRD) in Hematologic Cancers 
Rios-Olais et al. (2024) investigated the prognostic value of measurable residual disease (MRD) in CLL in a recent 
systematic review and meta-analysis. The evaluation was comprised of only prospective trials (n = 11) reporting 
progression free survival (PFS) by MRD status; MRD was assessed via varying highly sensitive techniques (e.g., 10
−4
 or 
one per 10,000 cells), including multiparameter flow cytometry (MFC), allele-specific oligonucleotide polymerase chain 
reaction (ASO-PCR), and NGS. A total of 2765 individuals that had undergone treatment with targeted therapies or 
obinutuzumb-based regimens were included. Results of the analysis revealed that participants who achieved an 
undetectable MRD had significantly longer 24-month PFS than those with detectable MRD [91.9% (95% CI, 88.8%-
95.2%) vs 75.3% (95% CI, 64.7%-87.6%); p < .001]. This was particularly evident in the first-line treatment setting as well 
as with time-limited therapies. However, the use of different MRD detection methods and tissues (with varied sensitivity 
and specificity) could impact direct comparison and potentially affect reliability of pooled results. In addition, the timing of 
MRD assessment was variable across studies, and some trials did not test for MRD unless the participant achieved a 
complete response, which introduces bias. Lastly, the study was restricted to specific therapy types and the majority of 
studies focused on PFS rather than overall survival (OS), which is a more definitive clinical outcome. Despite these 
limitations, the authors determined that based on their large systematic review and meta-analysis, MRD status is strongly 
associated with PFS in individuals with CLL and support the use of MRD as a surrogate endpoint in the setting of clinical 
trials. They advocate for the standardization of MRD assessment in both research and clinical practice. 
 
The measurement of MRD played a central role in guiding treatment decisions for participants with relapsed/refractory 
CLL in the CLL2-BZAG trial (Fürstenau et al., 2025). CLL2-BZAG was a phase 2 trial which enrolled 42 participants (two 
were excluded per study protocol) with relapsed/refractory CLL who received treatment with zanubrutinib, venetoclax, and 
obinutuzumab after optional bendamustine debulking; the duration of therapy was tailored based on MRD status 
(determined via high-sensitivity flow cytometry). MRD assessment occurred at regular intervals for tracking depth of 
response and to guide treatment cessation. Participants had a median of one prior treatment (range = one to five 
treatments). Fifteen of the participants had a TP53 mutation/deletion and 31 had unmutated immunoglobulin heavy chain 
variable region gene (high risk genetic features). After six months of triple therapy, 100% of participants responded, with 
52.5% [95% confidence interval (CI), 36.1-68.5] achieving undetectable MRD in peripheral blood. Estimated 18-month 
PFS was 96% and estimated eighteen-month OS was 96.8%. In addition, no participants required further treatment during 
the observation period (median 21.5 months) and over time, undetectable MRD deepened; maximum undetectable MRD 
rate was 85% for the entire study population. Of note, COVID-19 had an impact on this study, affecting 26 of the 42 
participants, with two COVID-19-related deaths. The study was limited by its small sample size and the prior 
bendamustine debulking treatment of half of the participants, as well as the presence of high-risk features in a significant 
proportion of participants. Two participants with very early treatment discontinuations were excluded; this exclusion may 
have led to overestimation of the efficacy of the study treatment. In addition, MRD was measured primarily in peripheral 
blood, which may not fully reflect disease status in bone marrow or lymphoid tissues. Despite the limitations, the trial 
demonstrated high response rates and deep MRD remissions. The researchers suggest that the results of this study, in 
which the use of MRD measurements were vital, show promise for the use of an MRD-guided approach to treatment with 
zanubrutinib, venetoclax, and obinutuzumab as it resulted in deep remissions, high response rates, and durable disease 
control, even in participants previously treated with BTK inhibitors or venetoclax and/or with high-risk genetics, and 
allowed for time-limited treatment, which reduces potential toxicity.  

 
